Malaysia Stock Movers: CIMB, Eastern, Genting, IJM, IOI, Opcom

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n   a n d   G a n   Y e n   K u a n
-- 
2011-09-02T09:50:18Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-02/malaysia-stock-movers-cimb-eastern-genting-ijm-ioi-opcom.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. close.  Malaysia’s  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 26.82 points,
or 1.9 percent, to 1,474.09, the sharpest gain since March 8,
2010. Stocks resumed trading after a three-day holiday. The MSCI
Asia Pacific Index gained 2.8 percent in that time.  Plantation stocks: IOI Corp. (IOI MK) jumped 6.2 percent to
4.79 ringgit, its biggest increase since January 5, 2009, as
palm-oil prices climbed as much as 2 percent today.  Kuala Lumpur
Kepong Bhd. (KLK)   rose 1.7 percent to 21.68 ringgit, the
sharpest increase since May 26.  Genting Plantations Bhd. (GENP)   gained 3.3 percent to 7.30 ringgit, while  IJM Plantations
Bhd. (IJMP)   rose 1.9 percent to 2.72 ringgit.  CIMB Group Holdings Bhd. (CIMB)  , a Malaysian banking
group, gained 4.7 percent to 7.40 ringgit, the biggest increase
since July 31, 2009. Deutsche Bank AG upgraded the stock to
“buy” from “hold” with a share-price target of 8.20 ringgit.  Eastern and Oriental Bhd. (EAST MK), a property developer,
rose 7.4 percent to 1.60 ringgit, the sharpest advance since Aug.
1. Sime Darby Bhd. (SIME MK) agreed to purchase a 30 percent
stake in the company. This will enable it to tap into Sime’s
“massive” landbank and “strong” balance sheet, Yee Mei Hui,
an analyst at HwangDBS Vickers Research Sdn., wrote in a report.  Opcom Holdings Bhd. (OHB)  , a supplier of fiber optic
cables, climbed 24 percent to 1.01 ringgit, the highest close
since August 16, 2005. The company said its shares will trade
ex-dividend on Sept. 14. Opcom earlier declared a special
dividend of 22.5 sen per share.  To contact the reporters on this story:
